< gmap_id>
0x809012a3d1bc8f27:0x4fa33e6cc0d5d0bc<//gmap_id>
< Text>
I suffered several strokes in March and was sent home from another hospital with vertigo, even though the CT scan clearly showed them.
Two days later, I ended up at SJGH.
While I don't remember going into the hospital, I required emergency brain surgery, as I'd had a massive hemorrhagic stroke.
The nurses were on strike but, I ended up with an awesome traveling nurse in ICU and my family loved him. His name is Joel.
My neurosurgeon, Dr Darby Invergo, saved my life.
Was everything perfect? No. But, I was well cared for. I stayed in ICU for about a week and was transfered out one evening when the COVID guidelines went into effect, on approximately day 10-12.
This is a teaching hospital and many of the docs come in from Stanford, UCDavis and UCSF one or two days a week.
I was completely unable to care for myself but someone came everytime I needed attention, on top of coming in regularly. They were very patient with me and calmly explained things repeatedly.
I have had a long haul and several follow-up appointments that turned into an urgent referral to UCSF, as the heart procedure I required is not performed at the county and my history was such that I needed more than St Joseph's could offer.
It was not seamless and I had to stand my ground with the cardiologist.
I saw a phenomenal hematologist there and she made sure that I got my test results ASAP after we had an in depth visit.
COVID definitely changed the game as far as getting into the clinics, requesting medical records, etc. My urgent referral still took 2.5 months. I got a CD of my heart test IN PERSON in the cardiololgy clinic and paid to send it to UCSF so the doc would be able to study it but people at the hospital advised me what to do and why. Even a customer service rep gave me the most helpful information.
I have HPSJ and a case manager, the latter really helped.
The hospital does have an antiquated computer system.
But, they saved my life!</Text>

After about a hour of waiting she checked me and I was 8 centimeters dialated to her surprise. The nurse kept leaving I was in so much pain by about 3pm my husband arrived and my friend and him kept having to call the nurse to check on me, she would just say they were busy and there was nothing they could do so they upset all of us and my husband and friend argued with them to come help me. < Text>
A 15 year just passed away at this hospital, read below ...   grieving Stockton family claims San Joaquin General Hospital staff's negligence led to a 15-year-old's death.

Yunique Morris died last Thursday.

The 15-year-old was a healthy, active student and cheerleader at Weston Ranch High School in Stockton.

Two weeks ago, Yunique complained of ongoing chest pain and was seen by her doctor at San Joaquin General Hospital,KTLA sister station KTXL¬†reported Friday.

Speaking to the Sacramento-area television station, Yunique's grandmother, Wanda Ely, said the teen's doctor diagnosed her with chest wall pain. She was given pain medication and antibiotics then placed on bed rest.

‚ÄúHer health just started going downhill," Ely said. "It got to the point where she couldn‚Äôt even go up and down a flight of stairs without getting out of breath.‚Äù

A few days later she returned to her doctor. The family said the doctor insisted her illness was minor and she was experiencing inflammation.

Yunique's mother was still concerned, so she asked for an X-ray. Days passed, but Yunique's health did not improve.

‚ÄúShe felt nobody is helping her and she didn‚Äôt really understand what was going through her body, but she knew something wasn‚Äôt right," Ely said.

Then last Thursday Yunique sent her mother an urgent text message.

"I NEED TO GO TO THE HOSPITAL, I JUST PASSED OUT, I‚ÄôM THROWING UP NOW," the message read.

Her older brother rushed her to the emergency room at San Joaquin General where doctors found numerous blood clots in her chest. She died within hours.

Devastated by the teen's death, Ely and her family are looking for answers.

An autopsy is being conducted at the Children's Hospital in Oakland. The family said a cause of death won't be known until at least late next week.

An administrator with the hospital told KTXL that the hospital could not comment on the incident because of patient confidentiality.< /Text>

<Review>I waited to write this review until everything was delivered and up and running. First let me say thank you to everyone working at Spa Max and a big shout out to Frank. From beginning to end he has been great with communication and has put up with my continuous questions.

I ordered my Cal Spa back in the middle of July. I didn't quite fully understand how much the spa industry was impacted by Covid. Orders for spas were through the roof and the factories are all having to scramble to fill orders while still keeping everyone safe and following the regulations. We were quoted an 8 week lead time but warned things could change. They did! Unfortunately the factory sent out multiple delays. Each time frank communicated with me. This was important to me. I understand things happen, especially right now. If I hadn't received that communication I would have been upset. Frank was great. I didn't always get the update I wanted to hear but at least I got something. We always had good conversations.

Finally my time had arrived and my spa was finished. I got my delivery date scheduled. The Spa Max delivery team arrived and went to work. They too were great. They positioned my spa exactly where I wanted and got everything set up. Frank was able to get me some extras as a thank you for being understanding and patient during the longer than usual wait.

The delays taking place right now  are not the dealers fault. Manufactures are trying to keep up but it going to be a long road to get there. Be patient everyone. It will be worth the wait.

Thank you again Spa Max for the great service.</Review>< user>

<UserId.>110336689691948214625<//UserId.><time>1496605759844</time><Rate>5< /Rate><text>I have not owned a Hot Tub before, and decided now was the time - a retirement necessity - LoL.
My initial impressions of Rick's Spas were - # Large showroom, with a large assortment of makes and models.  # We were greeted at the door, and encouraged to ask questions  when we were ready.  # No sales pressure at all.
After we narrowed our search down to four tubs that suited our requirements, we began asking questions.  I did a fair amount of research before even going to look, so I began with questions we already knew the answers to - you know - "testing the waters".  These guys know everything about every make and model they carry.  The pros, the cons, and the reasons why.   They do not have a hidden agenda for "pushing" one brand over another.
There were several "used" spas on display, but my preference is the same as buying a car....Buy new - you do not want somebody else's problems or leftovers, and common sense tells me that you do not know how the tub was previously maintained or used, and some problems are not initially apparent - so we shopped for new ones.
Their prices were on par, with a nice discount for cash purchase on a hot tub.   Delivery,  cover,  steps and start up chemicals are included in the price.  This alone set them apart from "other" stores I have been to - who charged for these in addition to the price of the tub.
We narrowed our choice down to two tubs , and decided to research both a bit further before purchasing one.  We came back the following day - our selection being made.  We selected the colors, paid, and were given a 3-4 week window since the tub is manufactured in Oregon and shipped here.
The only "hiccough" was - it actually took 5 weeks for the whole process, and I had to call at the 4 week mark to check on delivery status.  My spa was delivered and set up exactly 5 weeks after ordering.  My only critique is - I should not have had to call Ricks Spas.
I am very happy with my Hot Tub, and highly recommend  Spa Max (Ricks Spas) to anybody who are considering getting a Hot Tub.  You get great prices, large variety, and no "surprise" costs at the end.< /text><response>None<//response><GmapID>0x80dcc8ee50e9cbd3:0x7fc3aa92e58b517b</GmapID><Pictures>None< /Pictures><name>Diane Beard-Enrique< /name></record>

I had no idea what kind of spa I was looking for when I walked in the door to Spa Max (formerly Rick's Pool/Spa).  Fortunately they had a HUGE inventory.  Seriously... My legs were getting tired by the time I had walked around to see all the different makes & models of spa's.

The salesperson on the floor at the time was super helpful, I believe his name was Bobby...  Anyway, I had all kinds of 'newbie' questions since I hadn't done much research before walking in.  I'm the kind of person who very much likes to make my own decisions and don't appreciate being 'sold'.  That being said, I'm really glad Bobby made a few suggestions that definitely helped me out.  I'm a tall guy, about 6'3".  The tub I originally picked looked good to me, but Bobby pushed me towards a less expensive spa!  Seriously?  Yup.  He said that the seats were too shallow in the hot tub I was looking at and that:
1. My knees would come up to my chest when sitting down
or
2. I would spread my legs out and interfere with the seating of the person across from me.

I would never have thought of this on my own and I appreciated the non-aggressive, informative approach taken.  There were a number of other pieces of information they provided me through the decision making process - too many details to list here, but they definitely know their stuff.

I walked in thinking my budget was for a refurbished tub, which they have TONS of; but after discussing some financing options they were able to get me into a new tub!

It seemed like the refurbs were going for $2k on the low end, to about $5-6k on the higher end.  They also had new spa's going for $4k-$15k+.  You just need to weigh out what's important to YOU in regards to luxury, room, amenities, etc.

Paperwork, delivery, communication and overall experience?  I give them 5-stars.<//review>

< Text>
Loving my backyard. Can't wait for COVID to be over so I can have gatherings and show off my new backyard. For now, my toddler is loving walking or running around the backyard without worrying about tripping from the old slimy cement I once had. Yay pavers!

I worked with Jim, Frank, and Beau. First, Jim has a good vision which helps as most customers like me only know they want pavers and how much I can afford (though never tell contractors that). He measured the area, went over the colors and design, etc. Frank kept me in the loop on the schedule and Beau took care of me during the whole project. I am truly thankful for Beau as he worked with my last minute additions (sitting wall and lights). I mean I literally woke up and thought hmm "lights" and  here I go texting Beau. I think since my budget was limited, Jim just gave me what was most important to me and he truly stretched what I can reach with my budget.

The guys who worked on the pavers are like miracle workers, I mean I went to get a quick fast food brunch drive-thru and when I came back, the old stuff was mostly all taken down and its only been an hour or so. What they can do in 2-3 days was unimaginable. Yes, thats all the time it took and no they did not cut corners as I was observing the process from time to time. It was like HGTV live for me (I mean we all watch "Property Brothers" and the such but to see it in person was very entertaining). Yes, there was no way I could have DIY this backyard project and I wouldn't want to.

When it was all done, I was very happy. I'm also impressed by the warranty as when it started raining after a month and I discovered small area pooling water. I texted Beau and low and behold, I was penciled in very fast and it was fixed by the time it rained the next time. Their knowledge on how to fix problems was very helpful especially to someone like me who would leave things to professionals but watch so I can learn from their experiences.

To make my backyard better, I hired a tree removal company to remove a tree that was producing berries that started to stain my new pavers (Oh h*ll no). Unfortunately, the tree removal company cracked a brick and no they didn't tell me, I can just see some type of scratch mark on it and it wasn't the evening before they came. I knew it wasn't covered on the warranty but asked Beau if they can come and fix it. I was willing to pay but they were so nice that they came and fixed it for me for free. I think they felt bad as they knew my plans of how I wanted to show off my new pavers but with COVID, plans were still on hold. They have pride on their work, that small cracked brick would ruin the unveiling. Haha. Thank goodness. Yay, System Pavers.</Text>

It was a large scope of work, including demolition of existing concrete in the courtyard and backyard covered patio areas, 3 separate waterfall features, a firepit, artificial turf, covered pergola and extensive amount of hardscape with pavers.

<Text>This review is for System Pavers Project Manager Frank Gori.

I had some warranty work that needed to be done with paver work that had been installed by System Pavers. The person that responded to my call was Project Manager Frank Gori.

We looked over the work that needed to be done. After that was complete, Frank noticed that we had begun to tear out our artificial turf that had been installed by System Pavers. We have been having huge problems with smells that are coming from the turf. System Pavers had replaced the turf to try and eliminate the problem, but unfortunately that didn't work. System Pavers stated that they couldn't/wouldn't do anything further.

I explained the situation to Frank and he stated that he would do some checking and get back to us with anything he found out. He went to his superiors and explained to them the problem. He even brought one of them (Brent I believe) to the house. Brent stated that he, like Frank, didn't want us to have a bad experience with System Pavers. He offered to replace the turf at cost for us. Brent stated that there is a new turf out that may help with the problem.

<name>Olga B<//name><Date>1515637990997< /Date>< rating>
5</rating>
<text>A small isle of Ukraine in the heart of Santa Monica :) Come here to experience some ethnic spirit and to get some really delicious pickles and sausages! Indeed, american sausages and pickles are not at all like Russian/Ukrainian. You have to taste them to understand the difference. In fact, if you ask, the staff would be happy to cut you a little piece of any deli they have, so that you could choose. The staff are very polite and cheerful, even though they may look a bit grumpy at first - this is just a national trait of the russian character. All you have to do is to be polite yourself, tell them a story, and they would be your best friends! ;)
Once you become friends, they would always tell you whether the food you are choosing is fresh or not really and when they are expecting new deliveries or what are their own favorite products.
This is truly a very specific experience of shopping you would never get at Vons or Wholefoods!! :)< /text>< Pictures>

Annie Kolumski</Name>
<Time>1497144363627<//Time>< Rate>
2< /Rate>
<Review>Not very friendly staff, at least not some of them. The other staff I've seen have generally been reasonably polite, but the most recent one - a young-ish lady w/ long blond hair, essentially lied to me about the time to make me cut my shopping short and leave quickly.

I certainly expect better customer treatment; which doesn't include being rudely interrupted in my shopping & nearly kicked out when it's actually still about 10 min to closing.

I came in around a quarter till 8pm & spent 2 min choosing among the boxed candy - yes: 2. entire. minutes: how terrible of me...
The very second I turned toward the deli counter, the saleslady very pointedly & impatiently "asked" me if I was finally done & "urged" me to finish shopping, saying they were already about to close.

I thought this was quite odd since I knew I'd come in w/ plenty of time to get a few items & be out before closing, but was too polite to pull out my phone right in front of her to check the time. So I chose a couple of deli items in a hurry, while the saleslady's acting like this is all a giant inconvenience.

Then after everything got rung up & packed, & after I paid, & after I put everything in my bag, & after leaving the store; I pull out my iPhone - and what does it say? It's 7:55. Meaning it had been ~7:50 when that saleslady told me they were already closing.
Um: they close at 8pm, & they don't shut the doors early as far as I've seen on prev. visits there; or at least they're really not supposed to.

I'm a regular customer here, & I go to a lot of trouble to get here as it's not at all close to where I live, work or study & because their closing hours are a lot earlier than other grocers. Since I work & go to school it's very difficult to manage to come here when they're open: ~15 minutes before closing is the best I can do.
Despite that, I'm still always quick about it & always leave before they close. I come here almost weekly & overall I spend significant money at this very small store.

I will prob keep shopping here (due to the sheer lack of any other russian food store anywhere around), but if anyone tries to do that to me again I'm certainly not going to be too polite to pull out my phone right in front of their nose, turn the screen to them & sweetly ask 'oh, really, you're closing right now? Do you have a different time than this? Or have you changed your closing time from what's posted on your door?'

Pricing:
Their deli prices are average to high: Smoked salmon (packaged) is $14 for 11oz
Mackerel fish (whole, salted) $10+
–î–æ–∫—Ç–æ—Ä—Å–∫–∞—è –∫–æ–ª–±–∞—Å–∞ - $8/lb., which seems questionably high to me, & it tastes unpleasantly over-salted.

A major issue, however, is that not a single item in the deli counters has a price tag on it; so you have to ask for the price on every item you might be interested in buying (& none of the salesladies are particularly cheerful about answering), & then try to figure out right away in front of them whether that's a good price for you.
It gives the whole thing an unpleasant haggling overtone & makes you embarrassed to have to ask.
& of course since it's not written down anywhere; if you forget the prices you have to keep asking about every item at every visit. Or I guess you can just accept that they're going to charge you whatever they see fit & hope you've got enough to pay your surprise-amount bill when it's presented.

Also, they're often out of many popular types & flavors of boxed candy, sometimes for weeks or months at a time: so I waste my time making multiple trips without getting what I came for. When you ask about it they kind of just say 'yeah, we don't have anymore' (in russian); nothing about when (or if) the products will ever be there again: so you don't, u know, waste endless trips trying to buy it, like I've ended up doing. Just a kind of perpetual attitude of indifference, like they can do just fine without all of their customers.

Take from this what you will. But I think the fact that they're the only Russian food grocer in the entire Westside is the ONLY thing keeping them in business.</Review><Pictures>None</Pictures>< Resp>
None</Resp>

I currently have my own small business.  This is NOT how you handle mistakes.  I asked to speak to a manager.  The manager had the same attitude.  He told me what is done is done and had no interest making things right.   If one of my employees avoided responsibility like this, they would have been fired.  This was completely unprofessional.  I was so upset by this whole ordeal and wrong doing I left the store and called the corporate number.  I spoke to a receptionist.  She refused to take my name and number.  She told me they don‚Äôt handle thrift store issues.   She offered to give me the phone number of the thrift store I just left.  That made no sense.  I then emailed the Executive Director of the company.  No response from him either.   I‚Äôm left with the feeling the management and employees can do whatever they please with no accountability.  They will gladly take you donations and money but treat you with zero respect.  Without customers they wouldn‚Äôt  have a job.  Stop treating your  thrift store customers  like they are less than the people your organization is trying to help. Everyone deserves respect and non professional behavior should not be tolerated. Thank you.

<userid>113073531518435931028</userid>< Name>
Sarah Beaumont</Name>
<time>1580096302578</time>< rate>
3</rate>
< Text>
This is a boba place I have gone to quite a few times, and it has strongly made me want to write a review for this place because honestly, I have been disappointed by the quality of drinks for awhile now. When it first opened, their drinks were ok, but the more I came, the worst it got. Here's why- one time I ordered their Tiger Sugar Bubble Milk Tea and yes, while it was a new item, I had high expectations for it. It's new, so they should have at LEAST tested it out right? Wrong. The drink tasted bitter, and the iconic sugar syrup tasted like burnt rubber/sugar and felt like I was sipping on glue... All I know is... it did NOT taste good, and I would not order it again. I have ordered other versions of the Tiger Sugar Milk Tea at other boba places, and it has never tasted anything like THIS.... Then, yesterday, after a few months of not visiting Tbaar, I decided to head back because I was having a boba craving and was in the area at the time. I decided to order a Green Tea with Milk Foam and 75% sugar. The milk foam had a good balance of salt and cream, but boy, the Green Tea drink itself was NOT good. First off, there was no ice whatsoever in my drink, and I double checked my receipt to see if the male cashier wrote down no ice, and there wasn't any implication. Yet, my drink was lukewarm, and it tasted like I was drinking water- the tea was extremely diluted. Some of the boba balls were also somewhat hard to chew.  I don't know whether it was because I had a bad person making my drinks (I think it was always a specific male with glasses who made my drinks?), but every visit's been quite disappointing lately. I'm only giving it 3 stars because the ambience and interior design of the boba shop is actually really nice; it would be a good place to hang out to study or talk with friends. But for the drinks? Probably wouldn't be my first choice.<//Text>

< review>
The food quality was okay except that my waffle was barely warm. The service was marginal, and I was surprised that no half-and-half was available for my coffee, so I was offered non-dairy creamer (!) or heavy cream. The seating area was not in its old location, but rather within the adjoining Mexican restaurant, which was a tad creepy. The bacon and the sausages were quite good. My overall impression of this restaurant is that it has poor management, but the workers are doing their best to keep the ship afloat.</review>

The Waffle Spot is one of those restaurants that I think not many people know about. It definitely has a lot of variety and is a great pick if you‚Äôre a waffle and French Toast lover. I was relieved to find that there was outdoor seating available. During this covid era, some restaurants don‚Äôt have the space for it. My friend and I ordered the Sir Waffelot‚Äôs French Toast. It was topped with strawberries, an orange maple syrup as well as a cream cheese whipped cream. I added bacon, sausage, and eggs to the order too. Everything was delicious! I will definitely come back to try something different. If you want to satisfy that breakfast craving, try it out. Eat up!!!<//text>

<rating>5</rating>< Review>
Classic breakfast place. During COVID they are only serving out of one restaurant. Do you don‚Äôt get the same ambiance but the food is just as good. The Waffle Spot draws a lot of locals as well as tourists. When you arrive check in and put your name down. Due to the small dining room and social distancing the wait might be longer. You can scan the menu outside so once inside your ready to order.

The menu features eggs, waffles, and other classic breakfast favorites. You won‚Äôt get anything unique or special here. The food is fresh and well prepared.

If your staying in the hotel I‚Äôd recommend calling and ordering take out.  It will be less social interactions and will save you time.  You could also eat in the pool area.

Ample parking out front. Staff is friendly. They have a few hand sanitizer stations inside.< /Review>

<user_id>110864430240357292458< /user_id><Name>Lindsey Olson</Name>< time>
1552615872534</time>
<rating>4</rating>< Text>
My favorite country potatoes and waffles are the ones at the Waffle Spot! We've stayed at King's In a few times now and had breakfast every morning (and lunch one time) at the Waffle Spot during our stay. It's not a continental breakfast included with the hotel stay, but as a result you get way better quality food.

Our favorite things on the menu by far are:
- the waffles (we've had regular, blueberry, and banana nut), which are more flavorful and dense than I'm used to waffles being (not quite as dense as a cake donut, but these are to normal waffles as cake donuts are to normal donuts), and
- the country potatoes, which are cooked and seasoned to perfection (veggies cooked crispy in places but still with some fresh veggie crunch, and just the right amount of seasoning to make every bite flavorful).

Tip: Arrive early in the day to avoid a wait (or else assume you'll need to wait for a table or get your food to-go to take back to your room). We were used to being seated right away at the beginning of our trip when we were still waking up early enough to arrive when it opened at 7am, and then surprised to see a wait toward the end of our trip when we'd adjusted to California time and were waking up later.

I'd give this review five stars for the waffles and potatoes alone, but I did remove one star because quality of some dishes can be hit or miss (every now and then the potatoes/veggies are overcooked, and the omelettes come out amazing half of the time and at other times seem more like they mixed the veggies with the eggs to make a frittata to save time instead of folding in the veggies to make an omelette. I haven't kept track, but I'd guess the times when the quality wasn't as great might have coincided with when they were really busy, so that might be one more reason to go early in the day! Even with that caveat, I'd go back in a heartbeat; I already miss the waffles and country potatoes now that our trip is over! :)< /Text>

<Text>Amazing place to go for breakfast.
Huge breakfast menu here and everything cooked fresh to order.
Very family friendly, in fact friendly place all round.
We stayed at kings in for 5 days and had breakfast here four times, trying different things each time.
Yep, the waffles are awesome but there is a nice Mexican breakfast menu too.
The Mexican omelette is good and the country breakfast is also a winner.
Good drinks.
Can get busy here but there wait is never very long but worth it.
If you're looking for a decent breakfast in San Diego then jump in a cab and go here because it will be worth it!< /Text><pics>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPxPJXEEEhcfE99WezJ-Pz3KUQjWGQNQhpPWDxf=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPxhXyYoMWDH8v6m9zkiK319hF96F5Km7Zi0qGg=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNhs7yhgifKCzA40rPRLQI2Kz8-FlKrVJ_0aQzp=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMlWYSQ5lkhmGJIE-v40HOiBWUDfjV6XOp0s_dg=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNryyIZ8VyblkyGffLyi0ch-wO_d_eiK5YZDw6P=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipOBdGcMSfMNzLSOa9WfkaB96Np_Pp58XLAkXshJ=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMey8Th0Sivo6IK8bvRb_tbQT_mZ989LXLTs04F=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipP9m8Y7-HEw3oYEik93-0f6w63iFxfQV0rn34xE=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMV1W5r3ubhTARQiO46arcJlqd0D97EU2u9yPxd=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipN3hj0g5dQfUsfz58qp6x70bz6kAikapHzDSzlW=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipO0or0XAI2q6G8rSS6hWpgg68_qC6ikBsPbangl=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipOROZKKAQbiUTPgtv_iaSMnwdUsM1p8hpLexmLI=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]< /pics><Resp>None< /Resp>< Gmap_id>

<date>1563128099436<//date><Text>After a 10 minute waiting line I got a chance to finally get inn and try out the food.  I was seated at the counter and was quickly offers something to drink.  The menu had several iluatrations of the waffle spot royal family, cute but not really helpful.  I ordered an apple and cinnamon waffle with a side of bacon and unsweetened iced tea.

Food was way better than what I expected it to be, one single waffle was more than enough and the extra bacon turned out to be to much ( I left a single strip our of the 5 handled to me).   I can still taste the cinnamon and the sliced apple with the melted butter, delicious. I was left to wander why they only offered one syrup, a wider variety would go well with their different waffle options.

The staff was great, quick, clean and ready to serve me if I needed something extra without being too pushy, an amazing and difficult quality to achieve.

Overall a great expirience.</Text>< username>

<Review>Get. The. Waffles.
Literally stumbled into this popular spot on accident - best thing that could've happened - so glad it did. Super cute and so tactfully well-maintained, very decent service which is always nice, but the food guys - the food. First of all they have hash browns - yay. Everything was well-seasoned and well-portioned and for a perfectly reasonable price. Huge bonus  - they're smart enough to offer the option of mini waffles with any of the meals and that mini waffle made me say f* a moderately-healthy, delicious omelette, next time I'm getting a plate full of those waffles.
Best waffles I've ever had.
Be smarter and go early or if you can't or didn't, just be prepared for a bit of a wait for a little great spot and a chance to have those waffles.< /Review>< user>

<time>1555120017322<//time>< text>
This place is not just cute it also serves DELICIOUS FOOD! I personally love this place and have had many breakfasts with my mom here but my friend I took today is a picky eater. He ordered the chicken and waffles and I ordered the blueberry waffle platter. We both ordered coffee. The coffee is amazing. It almost has a chocolate undertone to it that maked me fall in üíò. My friend also loved the coffee and didn't care that there was no flavor creamer. His chicken and waffles gave me order envy. Next time I'm ordering that. He said this was the best chicken he has had. It tastes like meat. He also said that it was fried like REAL SOUTHERN fried chicken. It just fell right off the bone. He was happy that they has Louisiana Hot Sauce there. He ordered a pecan waffle and they did NOT skimp on pecans. He had some left even after the waffle was long gone. We both thought the waffles were out of thia world! I had an abundance of blueberries...real blueberries not the frozen or syrupy ones but fresh tasting berries. Mmmm. The waffle held up to all the syrup I drenched it with. I asked for crowns and they gave us two that I managed to talk my friend into wearing with me. They also have a color Sir Waffle Lots face on a placemat. Adults have to ask for one but kids automatically get one. They have some very talented guests that have left their mats that are hung on the wall. Make sure to take photos on the way in or out with Sir Waffle Lot. Our server was fantatsic..always checking on us and the other tables around us and she kept pur coffee cups full. I'm looking forward to going back.<//text>

<Review>I have to admit that I didn't want to try this place for our last breakfast while on a short birthday weekend after seeing the pictures online. I would have preferred to go to Snooze because of the more adult looking decor, but I was out voted. Our Lyft ride from downtown was about 10 minutes but it was a nice scenic ride over to that area of town. The restaurant is actually connected to an outside motel. The decor was not as childish as I thought and the place was  very clean. We were seated quickly.  As we were deciding from the many options,  I was  checking out the size of the plates coming out...Huge!! Our server gave us all of the pros and cons of what we were considering.  The service was great..never had to ask for a refill. The food came fairly quick..maybe 10 minutes. We liked the presentation and taste of our food. Would definitely recommend and maybe return if ever in SD again. Prices were also very good.< /Review>< UserId.>

< review>
What a fantastic little spot for breakfast and lunch! We loved the diner vibe, 50s and 60s music, great food, and super friendly staff. Our server, Paula, was especially sweet and attentive. I had the Pumpkin Spice Waffle Platter and hubs had the regular Waffle Platter. "Platter" just means you get 2 eggs, 2 bacon strips, and 2 sausage links with your waffle. It was so much food, I had a hard time finishing it! That said, I really wanted to because it was sooooo goooood!! There's even a person dressed as the Waffle King who walks around waving at customers and throwing finger guns. I wish we'd taken a picture with him/her/them!< /review>

<rate>5< /rate><Gmap_id>0x80deaad363d4056b:0x565c36c3649108c2<//Gmap_id>< review>
My review from yelp on 5/7/2017
Came in very hungry with 3 of my friends. After 5 minutes of waiting, we got to sit at the Amigo Spot. The seats were very comfortable than many restaurants I sat because of the padding.
Our server was very kind and attentive to my 2 friends who decided to drink coffee. She was also very patient when it came to getting down my friend's order as we were still indecisive on what to get. The menu layout is very simple, but I do not recall seeing any pictures of the food on the menu.
I ordered the egg waffle benedict and it was delicious. I loved the fact that the waffle was on the bottom of the egg with some ham. The hashbrown was good for me, but my friend said it was okay. My friends loved coming here for them waffles. I like the fruit they gave me after eating the benedict. A great breakfast I had indeed.
Price wise, I think it cost a bit more than some places where I have breakfast. I can not complain though as it was filling.
Wait, I was not full. My friends were though (I eat more than the typical average person), so I had some freebies from my friends who did not finish their food. They were a piece of bacon, some mini waffles,more hashbrown and a slice of steak. It was delicious.
Since the location is in a hotel/inn, the restroom there also has free mouthwash you can use after eating. I thought it was unique so definitely giving them a 5 stars for nice, talkative and courteous waiter, for their delicious food, comfy seats, and the mouthwash I used in the restroom and more on the 4 stars for the pricing as I was not full, but that is just me.< /review>

< Date>
1524411433086</Date>
< Rating>
3</Rating>
<text>Located off the lobby of some random motel, this is a diner type restaurant that doesn't have too much seating. The menu has a variety of breakfast items, but less waffle items than you would imagine although it's called The Waffle Spot. I came early and sat at the counter, so there was no wait. Staff was good for the most part, but I think since I was at the entryway it was better than it would have been had I not been there.

I ordered the 2 egg breakfast, which I choose hash browns and 2 mini-waffles. The portion is not at all generous, I wouldn't call it stingy, but it's close to it. The hash browns were a 4x4 flat square, the eggs were good, and the waffles are really mini, however, they were pretty good, being soft, moist, and fluffy.

Overall, this is a standard breakfast place, it's not really special, there's nothing you can get here that you couldn't get at another breakfast establishment. The food is fine, but for me, it's not worth more than a 10 minute wait or an inconvenient drive.</text>< Pictures>
None</Pictures>
< resp>
None< /resp>

<Name>Toni Morse</Name>< review>
Delightful ending to a trip to San Diego when group I was traveling with wanted traditional American breakfast. What a great find!!! We stepped into the Waffle Spot and we stepped back in time to the days of motor hotels with in-house restaurants. You'll find true retro diner ambiance here in a freshly decorated, remodeled "motel" lobby. Their staff was friendly and welcoming and most customers seemed to be locals who know the quality of this local gem. We had the Baja omelette ... very good, but the mini waffles were AMAZING! Definitely hit the SPOT!!!  (Also, I asked to see a room in the hotel and was delighted to see a nicely appointed room w/ 2 queens, clean fresh white bedding, travel themed throw pillows, clean modern room, updated bathroom (though small) ... looks like a wonderful place to stay and at a great price and great food downstairs ... bfast, lunch, and dinner ... Waffle Spot on 1 side and Amigos on the other, a Mexican restaurant that I'm guessing boasts the same great food and service.</review>

<user_name>Sean O. Davis<//user_name><Date>1418584411396< /Date><rating>5< /rating>< text>
The waffles are AMAZING... And the rest of our meal (omelette and hash browns) equally so!!  Our server, Paula, is the sweetest.

It is an old school breakfast diner, and the food has that yummy yesteryear homemade goodness taste. The place was packed, which was a good indicator of how good it is. Would I come again?... Well, we drove across town to come back the second day we were in San Diego just to have some more!< /text>

< date>
1375991751504< /date>
<Gmap_id>0x80deaad363d4056b:0x565c36c3649108c2< /Gmap_id><response>None<//response>< Text>
The Waffle Spot was excellent!  Through a disaster at Orbitz, our hotel reservations were moved across the city to the Travelodge next door to the Kings Inn.  For the first couple of mornings, we passed by the Waffle Spot and poked fun at the over-the-top decor.  By the third day, we stopped in for breakfast and instantly regretted having waited so long.

The staff was very friendly and courteous.  We had some concerns regarding dietary restrictions and they were very willing to work with us.  The food arrived at our table promptly and was just as hot and delicious as the menu portrayed it.  The wait staff was very busy, but they did very well to keep our coffee cups full.

On a side note: we sat across from a table with small children and the wait staff was very flexible with changing orders, side dishes, and keeping extra napkins/water on hand.  I was very impressed.

Stop by and don't forget to say "hi!" to the Waffle King.</Text>

<userid>106844069025112550958<//userid><Pics>None< /Pics>< gmap_id>
0x80deaad363d4056b:0x565c36c3649108c2< /gmap_id>
<username>Steve Schwartz< /username><time>1523641824197<//time>< rating>
3</rating>
< response>
None</response>
< text>
Rube food. A rube is an innocent person, with little street smarts and a bright outlook. This place is intended to capture rubes. Like most of the joints attached to hotel/motels in SD, they really depend on a captive audience, who either walk, or don't know their way around San Diego. Since the stupid demise of Albie's/Adam's next door, I had hoped that this 'Spot' might have something left of the old school, since it has been here a long time. But no...

Waffles that I saw coming out we're uninteresting, at best, and the mini-waffles I chose instead of toast were undercooked and floury. Non-dairy chemical creamer for the coffee. Coffee itself was OK.

For $10.75, the Country Ham and Eggs sounded good (menu on Google Maps said $8.75, par for the course, never maintained), but the ham was as thin and tough as shoeleather. Potatoes were barely warm, and one of my over-medium eggs' yolk was busted under a corner of the ham shoesole.

Service was ok, but the toast-surrogate mini-waffles came late, when I had already nearly finished the rest. Like breakfast dessert.

Not a place I would return to. Nothing exceptional, nothing terrible. One good thing is that they seem to treat kids well, with crayons and coloring placemats.

You won't die. Or maybe I'll need to get back to you on that...</text>
</record>
</dataset><record>

<Resp>None<//Resp>< review>
Located in beautiful San Diego and nestled in the hotel circle is the Waffle Spot. Got here accidentally since we were trying to go to hash house but was very busy. Only took a few minutes to get seated even though they were very busy. I chose the churro waffle, why not, and added the platter 2 eggs sunny side ip 2 sausages and 2 pieces of bacon. The churro waffle delicious, very fluffy and sweet with a bit of a nice crunch did not need syrup. Customer service was great, always attentive and greeting with a smile. By far my favorite waffle spot.<//review>
<Pictures>None< /Pictures></record>
</dataset><record>
< rate>
3<//rate>
<Date>1447777086427</Date>< Review>
The waffles were excellent, one of ua got the pumpkin spice waffle and I got the waffles with chile. However,  there were egg shell pieces in the eggs and the bacon wasn't crispy. I thought anywhere calling themselves waffle spot might want to pride themselves better on other breakfast foods. Also, $3 for tea, which was a lipton tea bag, is a little bit much. The waffle king was there, which was a nice surprise!</Review>
